{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5b2c053e-8308-4b3f-9ffd-6d883133e28e","content":"With xUnit v3 + MTP, `dotnet test --filter` uses a **different filter syntax**. Two key changes:\n\n### 1. `FullyQualifiedName~` → `--filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests\"`\nThis part actually still works with MTP — the `~` (contains) operator is supported.\n\n### 2. `Category=Smoke` → `Trait=Category%3DSmoke` (or use `--filter-trait`)\nThis is the breaking change. MTP doesn't recognize `Category` as a first-class property. Traits are now filtered differently.\n\n### Your translated command\n\n**Option A — single `--filter` expression:**\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Trait=Category%3DSmoke\"\n```\n(`%3D` is the URL-encoded `=` inside the trait value.)\n\n**Option B — separate flags (clearer):**\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests\" --filter-trait \"Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nOption B is generally preferred because it avoids the encoding awkwardness and makes the intent explicit. Both flags are ANDed together.\n\n### Why it changed\nVSTest treated `Category` as a well-known alias for traits. MTP treats traits generically via `Trait=Key%3DValue` or the dedicated `--filter-trait` flag.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b5de66e2-af2a-46ec-ac0a-48ea46d39d7c","outputTokens":340},"id":"b051768e-ffb4-4273-a472-75c5e7d5bbe6","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:48:17.826Z","parentId":"603d437e-2009-4b53-94f3-bcc3feddc894"}
